      "rawMarkdown": "## 121. Aloof\n\n**Pronunciation:** ə-LOOF\n**Part of speech:** Adjective\n**Core meaning:** Distant, reserved, or emotionally detached.\n**Bangla meaning:** দূরবর্তী, বিচ্ছিন্ন, উদাসীন, গম্ভীরভাবে আলাদা থাকা\n\n**Root story / etymology idea:**\n*Aloof* likely came from old nautical language, connected with keeping a ship “to windward” or away from something. The original image is a ship staying apart from others. So, mentally: **aloof = keeping emotional distance.**\n\n**Simple explanation:**\nAn **aloof** person does not easily mix with others. They may seem cold, distant, or uninterested.\n\n**Memory hook:**\n**Aloof = alone + off** → someone stays “off” from the group.\n\n**GRE synonyms:** distant, detached, remote, reserved, withdrawn, standoffish\n**Basic synonyms:** cold, unfriendly, separate, not close\n**Antonyms:** friendly, sociable, warm, approachable, involved\n\n**Common usage:** aloof professor, aloof attitude, aloof manner, emotionally aloof, remain aloof from politics\n\n**Confusing word:**\n**Aloof ≠ Alone**\nAlone = physically by oneself.\nAloof = emotionally or socially distant.\n\n### Examples — 10\n\n1. The new student seemed **aloof** during lunch.\n2. The manager was polite but **aloof**.\n3. She stayed **aloof** from office gossip.\n4. The professor’s **aloof** manner made students hesitant to ask questions.\n5. Even after joining the committee, he remained **aloof** from its internal debates.\n6. The CEO’s **aloof** communication style created distance between leadership and employees.\n7. In academic discussions, an **aloof** tone may appear objective but can also seem dismissive.\n8. The diplomat remained **aloof** from the controversy to avoid appearing biased.\n9. Although the scientist was brilliant, his **aloof** personality limited collaboration.\n10. GRE-style: The candidate’s **aloof** demeanor, though interpreted by some as arrogance, was actually a defense against public scrutiny.\n\n### GRE Synonym Examples — 15\n\n1. The witness gave a **detached** account of the accident.\n2. The judge remained **impartial** and emotionally **detached**.\n3. The remote village was geographically **isolated** from major cities.\n4. His **reserved** personality made him difficult to know.\n5. The critic’s **distant** tone suggested little sympathy for the artist.\n6. She was **withdrawn** after the argument.\n7. The professor seemed **standoffish** at first, but later proved helpful.\n8. The committee adopted a **neutral** position during the dispute.\n9. His **remote** expression revealed no emotion.\n10. The aristocrat’s **haughty** reserve offended the guests.\n11. The analyst maintained a **dispassionate** perspective.\n12. The director was **unapproachable** during the crisis.\n13. The scholar’s **impersonal** writing style suited the scientific topic.\n14. The leader appeared **cold** toward public criticism.\n15. The official’s **detachment** helped him avoid emotional decision-making.\n\n**Common mistake:**\nDo not use **aloof** only for physical distance. It usually means emotional or social distance.\n\n**Final memory:**\n**Aloof = emotionally distant = দূরত্ব বজায় রাখা**\n\n---",
