      "rawMarkdown": "## 122. Clangor\n\n**Pronunciation:** KLANG-gər\n**Part of speech:** Noun\n**Core meaning:** A loud, harsh, repeated noise.\n**Bangla meaning:** কোলাহল, কর্কশ শব্দ, উচ্চ ধাতব আওয়াজ\n\n**Root story / etymology idea:**\n*Clangor* comes from Latin *clangere*, meaning “to resound” or “to make a loud metallic sound.” Think of metal hitting metal.\n\n**Simple explanation:**\n**Clangor** is not soft sound. It is loud, unpleasant, noisy, and often metallic.\n\n**Memory hook:**\n**Clangor = clang + noise** → metal doors banging loudly.\n\n**GRE synonyms:** clamor, racket, uproar, din, cacophony, tumult\n**Basic synonyms:** loud noise, noise, shouting, crash\n**Antonyms:** silence, quiet, calm, hush, stillness\n\n**Common usage:** clangor of bells, clangor of machinery, industrial clangor, street clangor\n\n**Confusing word:**\n**Clangor ≠ Clamor**\nBoth mean loud noise, but **clamor** can also mean loud public demand.\nExample: public clamor for reform.\n\n### Examples — 10\n\n1. The **clangor** of the bells woke everyone.\n2. We heard the **clangor** of metal gates.\n3. The factory was filled with the **clangor** of machinery.\n4. The **clangor** from the construction site made reading impossible.\n5. The morning market began with the **clangor** of carts, vendors, and traffic.\n6. The **clangor** of political slogans drowned out the speaker.\n7. In urban studies, noise pollution often includes the daily **clangor** of transportation.\n8. The poem contrasts rural silence with the industrial **clangor** of the city.\n9. The laboratory’s calm atmosphere was suddenly broken by the **clangor** of falling equipment.\n10. GRE-style: The reformer’s quiet proposal was lost amid the **clangor** of partisan accusations.\n\n### GRE Synonym Examples — 15\n\n1. The **clamor** of the crowd filled the stadium.\n2. Public **clamor** forced the minister to respond.\n3. The children created a terrible **racket** upstairs.\n4. The political rally descended into **uproar**.\n5. The city’s morning **din** exhausted the villagers.\n6. The orchestra produced a painful **cacophony** during rehearsal.\n7. The meeting ended in **tumult**.\n8. The machines **resounded** through the workshop.\n9. The alarm bells **clanged** throughout the building.\n10. The marketplace was full of **commotion**.\n11. The protesters’ **outcry** reached parliament.\n12. The crash produced a metallic **clatter**.\n13. The announcement caused immediate **uproar**.\n14. The school hallway echoed with **noise** after the bell.\n15. The factory floor was dominated by mechanical **clamor**.\n\n**Common mistake:**\nDo not use **clangor** for pleasant music. It usually suggests harsh, loud, unpleasant sound.\n\n**Final memory:**\n**Clangor = harsh loud noise = কর্কশ কোলাহল**\n\n---",
