      "rawMarkdown": "## 125. Diminutive\n\n**Pronunciation:** dih-MIN-yuh-tiv\n**Part of speech:** Adjective / Noun\n**Core meaning:** Very small; tiny.\n**Bangla meaning:** ক্ষুদ্র, ছোট, খর্বাকার\n\n**Root story / etymology idea:**\n*Diminutive* comes from Latin *diminuere*, meaning “to lessen” or “make smaller.” It is related to *diminish*.\n\n**Simple explanation:**\nA **diminutive** object, person, or form is very small.\n\n**Memory hook:**\n**Diminutive = diminished size.**\n\n**GRE synonyms:** tiny, petite, miniature, small, little\n**Basic synonyms:** very small, short, little\n**Antonyms:** huge, enormous, gigantic, massive, large\n\n**Common usage:** diminutive figure, diminutive size, diminutive village, diminutive form\n\n**Confusing word:**\n**Diminutive ≠ Diminish**\nDiminutive = small.\nDiminish = to reduce.\n\n### Examples — 10\n\n1. The **diminutive** kitten fit in my hand.\n2. She wore a **diminutive** silver ring.\n3. The village had a **diminutive** school.\n4. The **diminutive** device stored a surprising amount of data.\n5. Despite his **diminutive** stature, he spoke with confidence.\n6. The museum displayed **diminutive** models of ancient ships.\n7. In biology, some island species evolve into **diminutive** forms.\n8. The engineer designed a **diminutive** sensor for medical devices.\n9. The critic admired how the **diminutive** poem carried emotional weight.\n10. GRE-style: The machine’s **diminutive** frame belied its extraordinary computational power.\n\n### GRE Synonym Examples — 15\n\n1. The **tiny** seed grew into a large tree.\n2. The **petite** dancer moved gracefully.\n3. The artist built a **miniature** castle.\n4. The **small** sample limited the study’s conclusions.\n5. The child held a **little** glass bird.\n6. The **compact** device was easy to carry.\n7. The scientist examined a **minute** particle.\n8. The **microscopic** organism could not be seen without a lens.\n9. The **undersized** room felt cramped.\n10. The **slight** figure moved silently through the hall.\n11. The **pocket-sized** manual contained essential formulas.\n12. The **mini** drone flew indoors.\n13. The **modest** apartment had only one room.\n14. The **scaled-down** model helped engineers test airflow.\n15. The **wee** child smiled at the audience.\n\n**Common mistake:**\n**Diminutive** often sounds more formal than “small.” Good for GRE, academic writing, and literary description.\n\n**Final memory:**\n**Diminutive = very small = ক্ষুদ্র**\n\n---",
