      "rawMarkdown": "## 127. Enigmatic\n\n**Pronunciation:** eh-nig-MAT-ik\n**Part of speech:** Adjective\n**Core meaning:** Mysterious and difficult to understand.\n**Bangla meaning:** রহস্যময়, দুর্বোধ্য, ধাঁধাসম\n\n**Root story / etymology idea:**\n*Enigmatic* comes from Greek *ainigma*, meaning “riddle.” An enigmatic person or thing feels like a puzzle.\n\n**Simple explanation:**\nSomething **enigmatic** is confusing in a mysterious way.\n\n**Memory hook:**\n**Enigma = puzzle** → enigmatic = puzzle-like.\n\n**GRE synonyms:** mysterious, puzzling, inscrutable, cryptic, obscure\n**Basic synonyms:** strange, unclear, hard to understand\n**Antonyms:** clear, obvious, plain, transparent, straightforward\n\n**Common usage:** enigmatic smile, enigmatic statement, enigmatic figure, enigmatic results\n\n**Confusing word:**\n**Enigmatic ≠ Energetic**\nEnigmatic = mysterious.\nEnergetic = full of energy.\n\n### Examples — 10\n\n1. She gave an **enigmatic** smile.\n2. The note was short and **enigmatic**.\n3. His silence seemed **enigmatic**.\n4. The leader’s **enigmatic** answer confused journalists.\n5. The artist became famous for **enigmatic** paintings.\n6. The experiment produced **enigmatic** results that resisted easy explanation.\n7. In literature, an **enigmatic** narrator can create suspense.\n8. The archaeologists debated the meaning of the **enigmatic** symbols.\n9. The professor’s **enigmatic** comment forced students to rethink the problem.\n10. GRE-style: The politician’s **enigmatic** refusal to deny the allegation only intensified speculation.\n\n### GRE Synonym Examples — 15\n\n1. The cave contained **mysterious** markings.\n2. His response was **puzzling**.\n3. The judge found the witness’s behavior **inscrutable**.\n4. The message was **cryptic**.\n5. The poem’s meaning remained **obscure**.\n6. The scientist faced a **perplexing** anomaly.\n7. Her motives were **unclear**.\n8. The ancient ritual seemed **arcane** to outsiders.\n9. The philosopher’s argument was **abstruse**.\n10. The patient’s symptoms were **baffling**.\n11. The report contained **ambiguous** language.\n12. The smile was **mystifying**.\n13. The old manuscript was **impenetrable** to beginners.\n14. The data were **inexplicable** without further testing.\n15. The coded letter remained **unfathomable**.\n\n**Common mistake:**\n**Enigmatic** is not just “difficult.” It usually has a mysterious, puzzle-like quality.\n\n**Final memory:**\n**Enigmatic = mysterious like a riddle = রহস্যময়**\n\n---",
