      "rawMarkdown": "## 129. Extravagant\n\n**Pronunciation:** ik-STRAV-ə-gənt\n**Part of speech:** Adjective\n**Core meaning:** Excessively expensive, luxurious, wasteful, or beyond reasonable limits.\n**Bangla meaning:** অমিতব্যয়ী, অপচয়ী, অতিরিক্ত জাঁকজমকপূর্ণ\n\n**Root story / etymology idea:**\n*Extravagant* comes from Latin ideas meaning “wandering outside bounds.” Something extravagant goes beyond normal limits.\n\n**Simple explanation:**\nAn **extravagant** person spends too much. An extravagant plan may be too excessive.\n\n**Memory hook:**\n**Extra + vagrant** → going extra far beyond limits.\n\n**GRE synonyms:** lavish, excessive, wasteful, prodigal, immoderate\n**Basic synonyms:** costly, luxurious, too much, over-the-top\n**Antonyms:** frugal, economical, modest, restrained, simple\n\n**Common usage:** extravagant party, extravagant spending, extravagant claim, extravagant lifestyle\n\n**Confusing word:**\n**Extravagant ≠ Elegant**\nExtravagant = excessive or wasteful.\nElegant = graceful and tasteful.\n\n### Examples — 10\n\n1. The party was **extravagant**.\n2. He bought an **extravagant** watch.\n3. Her **extravagant** spending worried her family.\n4. The wedding was beautiful but unnecessarily **extravagant**.\n5. The company reduced **extravagant** executive bonuses.\n6. The critic rejected the author’s **extravagant** claims about originality.\n7. In economics, **extravagant** consumption can signal wealth but also waste.\n8. The project failed because its design was too **extravagant** for the budget.\n9. The proposal made **extravagant** promises without explaining practical steps.\n10. GRE-style: The mayor’s **extravagant** rhetoric concealed the modest scale of the actual reform.\n\n### GRE Synonym Examples — 15\n\n1. The palace was decorated in a **lavish** style.\n2. His **excessive** demands delayed the agreement.\n3. The prince lived a **prodigal** life.\n4. The banquet was **opulent**.\n5. The design was **ostentatious** rather than practical.\n6. The spending was **wasteful**.\n7. The claims were **immoderate** and unsupported.\n8. The hotel offered **luxurious** rooms.\n9. The celebration was **over-the-top**.\n10. The report criticized **reckless** borrowing.\n11. The billionaire’s house was **palatial**.\n12. The campaign’s promises were **grandiose**.\n13. The gift was **sumptuous**.\n14. The scholar warned against **unrestrained** speculation.\n15. The committee rejected the **inflated** budget.\n\n**Common mistake:**\n**Extravagant** can describe spending, style, behavior, or claims—not only money.\n\n**Final memory:**\n**Extravagant = beyond reasonable limits = অমিতব্যয়ী / অতিরিক্ত**\n\n---",
