      "rawMarkdown": "## 131. Frivolous\n\n**Pronunciation:** FRIV-ə-ləs\n**Part of speech:** Adjective\n**Core meaning:** Not serious, silly, or unimportant.\n**Bangla meaning:** তুচ্ছ, নগণ্য, হালকা, গুরুত্বহীন\n\n**Root story / etymology idea:**\n*Frivolous* comes from Latin *frivolus*, meaning “silly, trifling, worthless.” It suggests something lacking weight or seriousness.\n\n**Simple explanation:**\nA **frivolous** activity, complaint, or argument is not serious enough to deserve much attention.\n\n**Memory hook:**\n**Frivolous = free of value** → no serious value.\n\n**GRE synonyms:** silly, trivial, unimportant, petty, superficial\n**Basic synonyms:** childish, light, not serious, minor\n**Antonyms:** serious, important, weighty, meaningful, substantial\n\n**Common usage:** frivolous complaint, frivolous lawsuit, frivolous spending, frivolous behavior\n\n**Confusing word:**\n**Frivolous ≠ Fabulous**\nFrivolous = silly/unimportant.\nFabulous = wonderful.\n\n### Examples — 10\n\n1. He made a **frivolous** joke.\n2. She wasted money on **frivolous** things.\n3. The complaint was dismissed as **frivolous**.\n4. The court rejected the **frivolous** lawsuit.\n5. The teacher told students to avoid **frivolous** distractions before exams.\n6. The committee refused to spend time on **frivolous** objections.\n7. In legal writing, a **frivolous** claim lacks serious merit.\n8. The researcher criticized **frivolous** interpretations of complex data.\n9. The article argued that public debate had become too **frivolous** to address real problems.\n10. GRE-style: What appeared to be a **frivolous** anecdote later proved central to the historian’s argument.\n\n### GRE Synonym Examples — 15\n\n1. The issue was too **trivial** for a formal meeting.\n2. His **silly** behavior embarrassed the team.\n3. The objection was **petty**.\n4. The article focused on **superficial** details.\n5. The argument was **insubstantial**.\n6. The complaint was **minor**.\n7. The debate became **lighthearted** rather than serious.\n8. The committee ignored **irrelevant** remarks.\n9. The claim was **unimportant**.\n10. The criticism was **trifling**.\n11. The speech was full of **idle** chatter.\n12. The report dismissed **worthless** speculation.\n13. The student’s excuse was **laughable**.\n14. The novel was entertaining but **shallow**.\n15. The proposal lacked **substance**.\n\n**Common mistake:**\n**Frivolous** does not always mean funny. It means lacking seriousness or importance.\n\n**Final memory:**\n**Frivolous = not serious / trivial = তুচ্ছ**\n\n---",
