      "rawMarkdown": "## 133. Imperious\n\n**Pronunciation:** im-PEER-ee-əs\n**Part of speech:** Adjective\n**Core meaning:** Arrogantly commanding; acting like a ruler.\n**Bangla meaning:** দাম্ভিক, কর্তৃত্বপরায়ণ, উদ্ধত\n\n**Root story / etymology idea:**\n*Imperious* is related to Latin *imperium*, meaning “command” or “authority.” It suggests someone who behaves like an emperor giving orders.\n\n**Simple explanation:**\nAn **imperious** person acts superior and expects others to obey.\n\n**Memory hook:**\n**Imperious = imperial attitude** → behaves like an emperor.\n\n**GRE synonyms:** commanding, domineering, haughty, arrogant, overbearing\n**Basic synonyms:** bossy, proud, controlling, superior\n**Antonyms:** humble, modest, submissive, polite, respectful\n\n**Common usage:** imperious tone, imperious boss, imperious manner, imperious command\n\n**Confusing word:**\n**Imperious ≠ Imperial**\nImperial = related to empire.\nImperious = arrogant and commanding.\n\n### Examples — 10\n\n1. The boss spoke in an **imperious** tone.\n2. Her **imperious** gesture silenced the room.\n3. He gave an **imperious** order.\n4. The manager’s **imperious** style made employees nervous.\n5. The queen’s **imperious** manner intimidated visitors.\n6. The professor’s **imperious** dismissal of questions discouraged debate.\n7. In leadership studies, **imperious** authority often reduces team creativity.\n8. The official’s **imperious** response angered citizens seeking help.\n9. The novel portrays a ruler whose **imperious** behavior masks insecurity.\n10. GRE-style: His **imperious** demand for loyalty alienated even those who had once admired him.\n\n### GRE Synonym Examples — 15\n\n1. The general issued a **commanding** order.\n2. The manager became increasingly **domineering**.\n3. Her **haughty** expression offended the guests.\n4. The CEO’s **arrogant** tone weakened morale.\n5. The coach was **overbearing**.\n6. The ruler acted **authoritarian**.\n7. The official’s **dictatorial** style provoked resistance.\n8. He treated his assistants in a **supercilious** manner.\n9. The aristocrat sounded **patronizing**.\n10. The supervisor’s **bossy** behavior annoyed the team.\n11. The leader’s **autocratic** decisions ignored consultation.\n12. His **high-handed** approach failed.\n13. The monarch was **tyrannical**.\n14. Her **lordly** attitude made cooperation difficult.\n15. The judge’s **stern** command restored order.\n\n**Common mistake:**\n**Imperious** is stronger than “confident.” It means arrogant, superior, and commanding.\n\n**Final memory:**\n**Imperious = arrogantly commanding = দাম্ভিক কর্তৃত্বপরায়ণ**\n\n---",
