      "rawMarkdown": "## 134. Impertinent\n\n**Pronunciation:** im-PUR-tih-nənt\n**Part of speech:** Adjective\n**Core meaning:** Rude, disrespectful, or improperly bold.\n**Bangla meaning:** উদ্ধত, অভদ্র, বেয়াদব, অশোভন\n\n**Root story / etymology idea:**\n*Impertinent* originally meant “not relevant” from Latin *pertinere* = to pertain/belong. Later it developed the sense of behavior that does not “belong” in polite conversation—rude or improper.\n\n**Simple explanation:**\nAn **impertinent** remark is rude because it crosses a social boundary.\n\n**Memory hook:**\n**Impertinent = improper + rude.**\n\n**GRE synonyms:** rude, disrespectful, insolent, impudent, cheeky\n**Basic synonyms:** bold, disrespectful, bad-mannered\n**Antonyms:** respectful, polite, courteous, humble, deferential\n\n**Common usage:** impertinent question, impertinent remark, impertinent child, impertinent tone\n\n**Confusing word:**\n**Impertinent ≠ Important**\nImpertinent = rude or irrelevant.\nImportant = significant.\n\n### Examples — 10\n\n1. The child made an **impertinent** remark.\n2. His **impertinent** tone angered the teacher.\n3. She asked an **impertinent** question.\n4. The assistant was fired for **impertinent** behavior toward clients.\n5. The journalist’s question sounded **impertinent**, though it was legally relevant.\n6. The student’s **impertinent** interruption embarrassed the class.\n7. In formal settings, **impertinent** humor can damage credibility.\n8. The official dismissed the criticism as **impertinent**, though many citizens agreed with it.\n9. The novel’s servant is punished for an **impertinent** answer to the aristocrat.\n10. GRE-style: The scholar’s challenge was not **impertinent**; it was a necessary correction to a flawed argument.\n\n### GRE Synonym Examples — 15\n\n1. His reply was **rude**.\n2. The employee sounded **disrespectful**.\n3. The student’s **insolent** answer shocked the teacher.\n4. Her **impudent** smile annoyed the judge.\n5. The boy made a **cheeky** comment.\n6. The remark was **presumptuous**.\n7. His tone was **discourteous**.\n8. The guest’s behavior was **ill-mannered**.\n9. The comment seemed **inappropriate**.\n10. The question was **offensive**.\n11. The reply was **saucy** but amusing.\n12. The critic’s **irreverent** tone angered traditionalists.\n13. The assistant’s **brash** behavior cost him the job.\n14. The teenager gave a **flippant** response.\n15. The letter was **audacious** in its disrespect.\n\n**Common mistake:**\n**Impertinent** can mean rude, but in older/formal use it can also mean irrelevant. Context matters.\n\n**Final memory:**\n**Impertinent = rude / improperly bold = বেয়াদব**\n\n---",
