      "rawMarkdown": "## 136. Irresolute\n\n**Pronunciation:** ih-REZ-uh-loot\n**Part of speech:** Adjective\n**Core meaning:** Unable to decide firmly; uncertain or hesitant.\n**Bangla meaning:** দ্বিধাগ্রস্ত, অনিশ্চিত, সিদ্ধান্তহীন\n\n**Root story / etymology idea:**\n**Irresolute** comes from *in-/ir-* = not + *resolute* = determined. So **irresolute** literally means “not resolved” or “not firmly decided.”\n\n**Simple explanation:**\nAn **irresolute** person cannot make a firm decision. They hesitate, change their mind, or remain uncertain.\n\n**Memory hook:**\n**Irresolute = no resolution** → no firm decision.\n\n**GRE synonyms:** indecisive, wavering, hesitant, vacillating, uncertain\n**Basic synonyms:** unsure, doubtful, not firm, confused\n**Antonyms:** resolute, decisive, determined, firm, steadfast\n\n**Common usage:** irresolute leader, irresolute response, irresolute voter, irresolute policy\n\n**Confusing word:**\n**Irresolute ≠ Irrelevant**\nIrresolute = unable to decide.\nIrrelevant = not related.\n\n### Examples — 10\n\n1. He was **irresolute** about choosing a university.\n2. The manager looked **irresolute** during the meeting.\n3. Her **irresolute** answer showed that she was not confident.\n4. The committee’s **irresolute** response delayed the project.\n5. Investors disliked the CEO’s **irresolute** leadership during the crisis.\n6. The government appeared **irresolute** when quick action was needed.\n7. In research planning, an **irresolute** approach can waste time and resources.\n8. The candidate’s **irresolute** stance on taxation alienated both supporters and critics.\n9. The novel portrays an **irresolute** prince trapped between duty and fear.\n10. GRE-style: Although the evidence demanded immediate action, the board remained **irresolute**, postponing its decision until the damage was irreversible.\n\n### GRE Synonym Examples — 15\n\n1. The judge criticized the **indecisive** committee.\n2. Her **wavering** support weakened the movement.\n3. The minister gave a **hesitant** reply.\n4. The board’s **vacillating** policy confused employees.\n5. He remained **uncertain** about the safest option.\n6. The leader’s **tentative** plan lacked force.\n7. The student sounded **doubtful** during the presentation.\n8. The investor’s **ambivalent** attitude delayed the deal.\n9. The army could not afford a **faltering** command structure.\n10. The council’s **noncommittal** answer frustrated citizens.\n11. His **unsettled** mind made concentration difficult.\n12. The team became **unsure** after repeated failures.\n13. The negotiator’s **wavering** tone reduced trust.\n14. The researcher avoided **tentative** conclusions without data.\n15. The senator’s **vacillation** made his policy position unclear.\n\n**Common mistake:**\nDo not use **irresolute** for someone who is simply calm. It means weak in decision-making.\n\n**Final memory:**\n**Irresolute = unable to decide = দ্বিধাগ্রস্ত**\n\n---",
