      "rawMarkdown": "## 137. Laudable\n\n**Pronunciation:** LAW-duh-bəl\n**Part of speech:** Adjective\n**Core meaning:** Deserving praise.\n**Bangla meaning:** প্রশংসনীয়, সাধুবাদযোগ্য, প্রশংসার যোগ্য\n\n**Root story / etymology idea:**\n**Laudable** comes from Latin *laudare*, meaning “to praise.” Related word: **laud** = praise.\n\n**Simple explanation:**\nA **laudable** action is good, admirable, and worthy of respect.\n\n**Memory hook:**\n**Laud = praise** → laudable = praise-able.\n\n**GRE synonyms:** praiseworthy, commendable, admirable, meritorious, creditable\n**Basic synonyms:** good, noble, respectable, worthy\n**Antonyms:** blameworthy, shameful, disgraceful, objectionable, contemptible\n\n**Common usage:** laudable effort, laudable goal, laudable intention, laudable achievement\n\n**Confusing word:**\n**Laudable ≠ Laughable**\nLaudable = worthy of praise.\nLaughable = ridiculous.\n\n### Examples — 10\n\n1. Helping poor students is a **laudable** act.\n2. Her honesty was **laudable**.\n3. The volunteer’s **laudable** effort inspired others.\n4. The project had a **laudable** goal, even if its execution was weak.\n5. The mayor’s **laudable** plan to reduce pollution gained public support.\n6. The researcher’s commitment to transparency was **laudable**.\n7. In academic writing, acknowledging limitations is a **laudable** practice.\n8. The organization made a **laudable** attempt to improve rural healthcare.\n9. The policy’s intention was **laudable**, but its results were disappointing.\n10. GRE-style: Although the reform was **laudable** in principle, its vague implementation left many citizens skeptical.\n\n### GRE Synonym Examples — 15\n\n1. Her honesty was **praiseworthy**.\n2. The firefighter’s courage was **commendable**.\n3. The charity’s work was **admirable**.\n4. His patience was **meritorious**.\n5. The student’s improvement was **creditable**.\n6. The judge called the apology **honorable**.\n7. The team made a **worthy** effort.\n8. The professor praised the **noble** intention.\n9. The rescue mission was **exemplary**.\n10. The scientist’s caution was **responsible**.\n11. The reform was **well-intentioned**.\n12. The athlete’s discipline was **respectable**.\n13. The policy had **virtuous** aims.\n14. The article offered a **constructive** critique.\n15. The mayor’s environmental goal was **admirable**.\n\n**Common mistake:**\n**Laudable** describes something good enough to praise, but it does not always mean successful.\n\n**Final memory:**\n**Laudable = deserving praise = প্রশংসনীয়**\n\n---",
