      "rawMarkdown": "## 139. Marginalize\n\n**Pronunciation:** MAR-jin-uh-lyz\n**Part of speech:** Verb\n**Core meaning:** To push a person or group to the edge of society, power, or attention.\n**Bangla meaning:** প্রান্তিক করা, গুরুত্বহীন করা, উপেক্ষা করা\n\n**Root story / etymology idea:**\n**Marginalize** comes from **margin**, meaning edge or border. To marginalize someone is to push them to the “margin,” away from the center.\n\n**Simple explanation:**\nWhen a group is **marginalized**, it is excluded, ignored, or treated as less important.\n\n**Memory hook:**\n**Margin = edge** → marginalize = push to the edge.\n\n**GRE synonyms:** exclude, isolate, relegate, sideline, alienate\n**Basic synonyms:** ignore, push aside, treat as unimportant\n**Antonyms:** include, empower, integrate, recognize, center\n\n**Common usage:** marginalize minorities, marginalize voices, marginalize workers, marginalized community\n\n**Confusing word:**\n**Marginalize ≠ Memorize**\nMarginalize = push aside socially/politically.\nMemorize = learn by memory.\n\n### Examples — 10\n\n1. The policy **marginalized** poor families.\n2. Some students felt **marginalized** in class.\n3. The report discussed **marginalized** communities.\n4. The committee ignored women’s voices and **marginalized** their concerns.\n5. Economic inequality can **marginalize** entire neighborhoods.\n6. The new law was criticized for **marginalizing** rural voters.\n7. In sociology, institutions may **marginalize** groups by denying access to resources.\n8. The historian showed how colonial systems **marginalized** local languages.\n9. The organization tried to include people previously **marginalized** by policy decisions.\n10. GRE-style: By treating dissenting scholars as irrelevant, the academy effectively **marginalized** alternative interpretations.\n\n### GRE Synonym Examples — 15\n\n1. The club **excluded** new members from decisions.\n2. The policy **isolated** rural communities.\n3. The manager **relegated** junior staff to minor tasks.\n4. The media **sidelined** the issue.\n5. The reforms **alienated** many workers.\n6. The committee **ignored** local objections.\n7. The system **disempowered** vulnerable groups.\n8. The report **minimized** their contribution.\n9. The law **disadvantaged** minority applicants.\n10. The discussion **dismissed** their concerns.\n11. The administration **pushed aside** critics.\n12. The policy **segregated** communities by income.\n13. The debate **devalued** local knowledge.\n14. The old system **suppressed** dissenting voices.\n15. The group was **excluded** from meaningful participation.\n\n**Common mistake:**\nDo not use **marginalize** for simply “make smaller.” It usually means social, political, or institutional exclusion.\n\n**Final memory:**\n**Marginalize = push to the edge = প্রান্তিক করা**\n\n---",
