      "rawMarkdown": "## 142. Prosaic\n\n**Pronunciation:** proh-ZAY-ik\n**Part of speech:** Adjective\n**Core meaning:** Dull, ordinary, lacking imagination.\n**Bangla meaning:** গতানুগতিক, নীরস, কল্পনাহীন, সাধারণ\n\n**Root story / etymology idea:**\n**Prosaic** comes from **prose**, ordinary writing that is not poetry. So prosaic means plain, ordinary, and not poetic or imaginative.\n\n**Simple explanation:**\nSomething **prosaic** is ordinary and dull, not exciting or creative.\n\n**Memory hook:**\n**Prose, not poetry** → prosaic = plain and dull.\n\n**GRE synonyms:** ordinary, dull, commonplace, mundane, unimaginative\n**Basic synonyms:** boring, plain, everyday, normal\n**Antonyms:** imaginative, poetic, exciting, original, inspired\n\n**Common usage:** prosaic language, prosaic reality, prosaic explanation, prosaic style\n\n**Confusing word:**\n**Prosaic ≠ Prolific**\nProsaic = dull/ordinary.\nProlific = producing a lot.\n\n### Examples — 10\n\n1. The story was **prosaic**.\n2. His writing style felt **prosaic**.\n3. The explanation was accurate but **prosaic**.\n4. The movie turned a magical idea into a **prosaic** drama.\n5. The poet disliked the **prosaic** language of official reports.\n6. The scientist offered a **prosaic** explanation for the strange light.\n7. In literature, **prosaic** detail can make a scene realistic but dull.\n8. The speech lacked imagination and sounded disappointingly **prosaic**.\n9. The committee rejected the proposal because it was too **prosaic** to attract public interest.\n10. GRE-style: What seemed mystical at first received a surprisingly **prosaic** explanation from the physicist.\n\n### GRE Synonym Examples — 15\n\n1. The task was painfully **ordinary**.\n2. The lecture was **dull**.\n3. The idea was **commonplace**.\n4. The work felt **mundane**.\n5. The design was **unimaginative**.\n6. The description was **plain**.\n7. The routine was **humdrum**.\n8. The essay was **banal**.\n9. The joke was **trite**.\n10. The explanation was **pedestrian**.\n11. The report was **matter-of-fact**.\n12. The office work was **routine**.\n13. The film’s ending was **predictable**.\n14. The argument was **conventional**.\n15. The style was **uninspired**.\n\n**Common mistake:**\nDo not confuse **prosaic** with “clear.” Clear writing can be good; **prosaic** suggests dull or unimaginative.\n\n**Final memory:**\n**Prosaic = dull and ordinary = গতানুগতিক**\n\n---",
