      "rawMarkdown": "## 146. Stigmatize\n\n**Pronunciation:** STIG-muh-tyz\n**Part of speech:** Verb\n**Core meaning:** To mark someone or something with shame or social disapproval.\n**Bangla meaning:** কলঙ্কিত করা, বদনাম দেওয়া, সামাজিকভাবে অপমানিত করা\n\n**Root story / etymology idea:**\n**Stigmatize** comes from Greek *stigma*, meaning a mark or brand. Historically, stigma was a mark of disgrace. So stigmatize = mark with shame.\n\n**Simple explanation:**\nTo **stigmatize** someone is to treat them as shameful or inferior because of a label.\n\n**Memory hook:**\n**Stigma = shame mark** → stigmatize = put a shame label.\n\n**GRE synonyms:** disgrace, shame, discredit, brand, denounce\n**Basic synonyms:** label badly, shame, insult socially\n**Antonyms:** honor, praise, respect, dignify, vindicate\n\n**Common usage:** stigmatize illness, stigmatize poverty, stigmatized group, stigmatize failure\n\n**Confusing word:**\n**Stigmatize ≠ Strategize**\nStigmatize = shame/label negatively.\nStrategize = make a plan.\n\n### Examples — 10\n\n1. Society should not **stigmatize** poor people.\n2. Mental illness is often **stigmatized**.\n3. The campaign tried not to **stigmatize** patients.\n4. Public failure can **stigmatize** young students unfairly.\n5. The policy **stigmatized** entire communities as dangerous.\n6. The media often **stigmatize** unemployment instead of analyzing its causes.\n7. In public health, fear of being **stigmatized** may prevent people from seeking treatment.\n8. The article criticized laws that **stigmatize** addiction rather than treating it medically.\n9. The researcher warned that careless language can **stigmatize** vulnerable populations.\n10. GRE-style: By portraying poverty as moral failure, the report **stigmatized** those it claimed to help.\n\n### GRE Synonym Examples — 15\n\n1. The scandal **disgraced** the official.\n2. The accusation **shamed** the family.\n3. The error **discredited** the researcher.\n4. The article **branded** the group as dangerous.\n5. The minister **denounced** the practice.\n6. The rumor **tarnished** her reputation.\n7. The label **defamed** innocent people.\n8. The campaign **vilified** its opponents.\n9. The poster **demonized** immigrants.\n10. The report **maligned** the community.\n11. The false story **slandered** the activist.\n12. The court cleared him of the **disgraceful** charge.\n13. The policy **marked** them as outsiders.\n14. The language **demeaned** the poor.\n15. The accusation **tainted** the organization’s image.\n\n**Common mistake:**\n**Stigmatize** usually means social shame, not simply criticism.\n\n**Final memory:**\n**Stigmatize = mark with shame = কলঙ্কিত করা**\n\n---",
